land"},"en":{"about 1135–3 March 1246":"about 1135–3 March 1246","1135–1246":"1135–1246","–Female":"Deceased","1160–1246":"1160–1246","1164–1246":"1164–1246","1101–1136":"1101–1136","1105–Female":"1105–Deceased","1215":"1215","1105":"1105","about 1160":"about 1160","1136":"1136","1224":"1224","1246":"1246","1135":"1135","1101":"1101","1164":"1164","about 1135":"about 1135","3 March 1246":"3 March 1246","1160":"1160","Sutton Bingham, Yeovil, Somerset, England":"Sutton Bingham, Somerset, England, United Kingdom","Yeovil, Somerset, England, United Kingdom":"Yeovil, Somerset, England, United Kingdom","Sutton Bingham, Somerset, England":"Sutton Bingham, Somerset, England",", , England":"England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Bingham","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Dorset) and Irish (County Mayo): habitational name from Bingham (Nottinghamshire). The placename is probably from an Old English folk-name <i>Bynningas</i> (‘the people associated with a man named <i>Bynna</i>’), or possibly from an unattested Old English word <i>bing</i> ‘a kettle-shaped hollow’, + Old English <i>hām</i> ‘homestead’.","Irish (Ulster, of Scottish origin): altered form of   Bigham  .","American shortened and altered form of various like-sounding Jewish surnames such as   Bingenheimer  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Ingham","meanings":["English (Yorkshire and Lancashire): habitational name from any of the places called Ingham, particularly in Lincolnshire, Norfolk, and Suffolk. The placename is from the Old English personal name <i>Inga</i> + <i>hām</i> ‘homestead’. In Yorkshire this name was sometimes confused with   Bingham   in the 18th century.","English (of Norman origin): variant of the obsolete Norman surname <i>Engaine</i>; see   Gain  ."]},{"name":"Bigham","meanings":["Scottish (Wigtownshire) and Irish: habitational name from either Bigholm in Beith parish (Ayrshire) or Bigholms in Langholm parish (Dumfriesshire). The second element of the placename is from Older Scots <i>holm</i> (Old Norse <i>holmr</i>) ‘islet’, ‘raised land in a marsh’, ‘a stretch of low-lying land beside a river; a meadow’. The first element may be an unattested Older Scots <i>bigge</i>, a shortened form of <i>bigging</i> ‘building’. The name was taken to Ulster in the 17th and 18th centuries, where it was used interchangeably with   Bingham  ."]},{"name":"Bingenheimer","meanings":["German and Jewish (from Germany): habitational name for someone from Bingenheim on the Eder river (Hesse). Compare   Bingham  ."]}]},{"name":"Ralph","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From a Norman French name, <i>Raulf</i>, a contracted form of the Germanic personal name <i>Radulf</i>, derived from <i>rād</i> ‘counsel’ + <i>wulf</i> ‘wolf’. The spelling with <i>-ph</i> is due to classical influence in the 18th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Ralf","meanings":["From a Norman French name, <i>Raulf</i>, a contracted form of the Germanic personal name <i>Radulf</i>, derived from <i>rād</i> ‘counsel’ + <i>wulf</i> ‘wolf’. The spelling with <i>-ph</i> is due to classical influence in the 18th century."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":80,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":89,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Ralph de Bingham Sr was born about 1135, in Sutton Bingham, Somerset, England, his father, William de Bingham, was 36 and his mother, Mrs William de Bingham, was 31. He had at least 2 sons with Mrs. Bingham. He died on 3 March 1246, in England, at the age of 112, and was buried in England."},"et":{"about 1135–3 March 1246":"umbes 1135–3. märts 1246","1135–1246":"1135–1246","–Female":"Surnud","1160–1246":"1160–1246","1164–1246":"1164–1246","1101–1136":"1101–1136","1105–Female":"1105–Surnud","1215":"1215","1105":"1105","about 1160":"umbes 1160","1136":"1136","1224":"1224","1246":"1246","1135":"1135","1101":"1101","1164":"1164","about 1135":"umbes 1135","3 March 1246":"3. märts 1246","1160":"1160","Sutton Bingham, Yeovil, Somerset, England":"Sutton Bingham, Somerset, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Yeovil, Somerset, England, United Kingdom":"Yeovil, Somerset, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Sutton Bingham, Somerset, England":"Sutton Bingham, Somerset, England",", , England":"England"},"fi":{"about 1135–3 March 1246":"noin 1135–3. maaliskuuta 1246","1135–1246":"1135–1246","–Female":"Kuollut","1160–1246":"1160–1246","1164–1246":"1164–1246","1101–1136":"1101–1136","1105–Female":"1105–Kuollut","1215":"1215","1105":